Introduction¶

For this project i have chosen to look at the TMDB dataset. This data was provided as part of the Udacity Data Analysis Nanodegree and originated from Kaggle. it was originally sourced from IMDB but was replaced after takedown request.

Two main questions were investigated in the project:

1- Which genres are most popular from year to year? 2- What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

In [10]:
# split the columns that contain the '|' character into multiple rows. 
str_split = '|'

# Calculate maximum length of piped ('|') values
df['max_len'] = df[['cast', 'production_companies', 'genres']].apply(lambda x: max(len(x[0].split(str_split)), len(x[0].split(str_split))), axis=1)
max_len = df['max_len'].max()

# Split '|' piped cell values into columns (needed at unpivot step)
# Create as many new 'cast_<x>' & 'genres_<x>' & 'production_companies_<x>' columns as 'max_len'
df[['cast_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)]] = df['cast'].apply(lambda x: pd.Series(x.split(str_split)))
df[['production_companies_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)]] = df['production_companies'].apply(lambda x: pd.Series(x.split(str_split)))
df[['genres_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)]] = df['genres'].apply(lambda x:pd.Series(x.split(str_split)))

# Unpivot 'cast_<x>' & 'genres_<x>' & 'production_companies_<x>' columns into rows
df_pv_cast = pd.melt(df, value_vars=['cast_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)],id_vars=['budget', 'revenue','director','runtime','release_date','release_year'])
df_pv_production_companies = pd.melt(df, value_vars=['production_companies_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)],id_vars=['budget', 'revenue','director','runtime','release_date','release_year'])
df_pv_genres = pd.melt(df, value_vars=['genres_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)],id_vars=['budget', 'revenue','director','runtime','release_date','release_year'])

# Rename upivoted columns (these are the final columns)
df_pv_cast = df_pv_cast.rename(columns={'value':'cast'})
df_pv_production_companies = df_pv_production_companies.rename(columns={'value':'production_companies'})
df_pv_genres = df_pv_genres.rename(columns={'value':'genres'})
df.head()

# Rename 'cast_<x>' values (rows) to be 'key' for join (merge)
df_pv_cast['variable'] = df_pv_cast['variable'].map({'cast_{}'.format(i):'genres_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)})

# Join unpivoted 'genres' & 'cast' dataframes
df_res = df_pv_genres.merge(df_pv_cast, on=['variable', 'budget', 'revenue','director','runtime','release_date','release_year'])

# Rename 'production_companies_<x>' values (rows) to be 'key' for join (merge)
df_pv_production_companies['variable'] = df_pv_production_companies['variable'].map({'production_companies_{}'.format(i):'genres_{}'.format(i) for i in range(max_len)})
# Join unpivoted (the previous dataframe) & 'production_companies' dataframes
df_res = df_res.merge(df_pv_production_companies, on=['variable', 'budget', 'revenue','director','runtime','release_date','release_year'])

# Drop 'variable' column and NULL rows if you have not equal pipe-length in original rows
df_res = df_res.drop(['variable'], axis=1).dropna(subset=['genres', 'cast','production_companies'], how='all',axis=0).reset_index(drop=True)

#here i use the df_res dataframe because i need every genre in a separate row.

#plot bar charts for each separete year
axes = df_res['genres'].hist(by=df_res['release_year'], figsize = (45,40), bins=22);

# Define a different color for the bars
colors = ['#1f77b4', '#ff7f0e', '#2ca02c', '#d62728', '#9467bd', '#8c564b', '#e377c2', '#7f7f7f', '#bcbd22', '#17becf','#1f77b4','#ff7f0e','#2ca02c' ,'#d62728','#9467bd','#8c564b','#e377c2','#7f7f7f','#bcbd22','#17becf']

for i, ax in enumerate(axes.reshape(-1)):
    # Define a counter to ensure that if we have more than 19 bars with a value,
    # we don't try to access out-of-range element in colors
    k = 0

    # Optional: remove grid, and top and right spines
    ax.grid(False)
    ax.spines['top'].set_visible(False)
    ax.spines['right'].set_visible(False)

    for rect in ax.patches:
        # If there's a value in the rect and we have defined a color
        if rect.get_height() > 0 and k < len(colors):
            # Set the color
            rect.set_color(colors[k])
            # Increment the counter
            k += 1

plt.show()

The previous figures show how to change the genres of movies most watched and most popular from year to year from 1960 to 2015

We note that no type of film is fixed over these years. Rather, all types of films change in proportion from year to year, due to several factors that will be mentioned later, such as the cast, director, runtime......etc.

Research Question 2 (What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?)¶

In [101]:
def line_chart(d, title, xlabel, ylabel):
    #plot and show the effect of the directors on revenue.
    d.plot(legend=True, figsize = (18,10));

    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel,fontsize = 15)
    plt.title(title,fontsize = 20 )
    plt.ylim(0, None)

    temp = [i for i in range(0,len(d), math.ceil(len(d)/35))]
    plt.xticks( temp, temp, fontsize = 11, rotation=45)    # changing x scale by own
    plt.show()

from datetime import datetime
# here i use the df res2 dataframe because i don't need multiple repeated row

# extract the month from the release_date
m = []
for value in df_res2['release_date']:
    datem = datetime.strptime(value, "%m/%d/%y")
    m.append(datem.month)
df_res2['month'] = m

# use groupby() function to show the summation of revenue for each month.
final_df = df_res2.groupby('month').revenue.sum() 

# sort my datadrame
final_df = final_df.sort_values(ascending=False)
final_df = pd.DataFrame(final_df)
final_df = final_df.reset_index()


plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.bar(final_df['month'], final_df['revenue'],color=['tan','silver','fuchsia', 'red', 'green', 'blue', 'cyan','orange','darkgreen','violet','coral','violet'])

It is possible that these two months are the months of official holidays in many countries, or that these two months have important occasions or the date of the beginning of the spring and autumn seasons, and therefore the weather is mild. Which encourages people to get out of their homes and go to the cinema.

def scatterplot(data1, data2, title, xlabel, ylabel, ylim_1,ylim_2, xlim_1, xlim_2):
    plt.scatter(data1, data2 );
    plt.rcParams.update({'figure.figsize':(15,8), 'figure.dpi':100})
    plt.title(title,fontsize = 20)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel,fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel,fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylim(ylim_1,ylim_2)
    plt.xlim(xlim_1, xlim_2)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
    plt.show();

Conclusions¶

After this interesting analysis for the TMDb dataset and abstract conclusions after each analysis or visualization step here are some final thoughts:

For a Movie in order to be considered in a successful criteria

1- The budget has no significant impact on revenue. 2- The average movie time that people prefer and thus achieves high revenue ranges between 85 to 135 minutes.

3- You must choose the first 100 actors in the list you created above to earn at least 0.25e9 revenue.

4- You must choose the first 6 genres in the list you created above to achieve at least 704,27079.92 revenue.

5- You must select the first 135 production companies in the list you created above to achieve at least 0.30e9 revenue.

6- You must select the first 90 directors in the list you created above to achieve at least 0.2e9 revenue.

7- The film must be released during the month of December and June to ensure maximum revenue.

Limitation: 1- The revenue column does not have a currency unit, so it may be possible different movies have a budget in the different currencies according to the country they are produced in. So an inconsistency appears here which can state the complete analysis wrong.

2- International laws that differ from one country to another may prevent the showing of certain films within their country because these films violate the values and standards of their societies, or because of political differences with the country producing these films, and thus this directly affects the revenues, although the film may be successful in the country the other.
